tiles.markdown:
## Explanation

Number of concurrent lambdas running - gives an idea of our capacity to ingest events.

If we breach the threshold we can no longer process events.

## Thresholds

* Account limit is 3000
* Yellow is > 2100 aka 70%
* Red is a breach

When at red we can continue ingest while we increase our quota in the background

tiles.name: Markdown
tiles.markdown:
## Explanation

Number of events generated by producer.

If too many events are being delivered to our consumers, we can see which producer is having the biggest impact and throttle the rate of ingest for that specific producer.

## Thresholds

None

tiles.name: Markdown
tiles.markdown:
## Explanation

Approximate age of the oldest non-deleted message in the queue. The higher the value, the longer an event is sitting in the queue. The closer to 14 days it gets, the more likely it is to get deleted.

NOT ALL PRODUCERS HAVE SET THEIR QUEUE TO BE 14 DAYS.

If queue age gets older and older, then it indicates that we are not ingesting events quickly enough and we may breach our SLA with HMRC.

## Thresholds

* Yellow is > 10 seconds due to an HMRC NFR
* Red is > 7 days as this gives us a week to create a fix before events get deleted due to timeout

The limits are set so that we can be alerted while still having enough time to release a potential fix.

tiles.name: Markdown
tiles.markdown:
## Explanation

Number of events in the queue.

The higher the value, the more events there are in the backlog that need to be processed and the greater the strain on downstream services as a backlog is processed.

This metric is used to show the size of the backlog and the impact it will have on the downstream system.

## Thresholds

* Yellow is > 10 messages
* Red is > 1000 messages

Lambda may not instantly pick up events once they appear in the queue so SQS may show events in a queue but then milliseconds later, Lambda picks up the event.

Combined with SQS metrics being delayed by up to 1 minute, the yellow threshold of > 10 should take into consideration the behaviour of async processing happening near-instantly rather than instantly.

tiles.name: Markdown
tiles.markdown:
## Explanation

Our capability to read and write to DynamoDB.

How much capacity we have when we read/write to dynamoDB. If we breach our quota, then enrichment stops working

This metric is an indicator of if we are going to stop event being enriched

## Thresholds

* Account quota is 40000 for read/write
* Yellow is > 28000 aka 70%
* Red is a breach

We will still have capacity to increase our quota should we reach the yellow threshold. It also gives us an opportunity to implement throttling on event ingest without errors being thrown by Lambda.

tiles.name: Markdown
tiles.markdown:
## Explanation

The latency of successful requests to DynamoDB.

This is not useful for capacity but useful for debugging issues.

## Thresholds

None

tiles.name: Markdown
tiles.markdown:
## Explanation

Count of retries as measured messages received by the event enrichment DLQ.

This is not useful for capacity but useful for debugging issues.

## Thresholds

None

tiles.name: Markdown
tiles.markdown:
## Explanation

The number of events that we can send **into** SNS which affects the number of events we can send per second.

This determines how many events we can send to our consumers before breaching an AWS quota.

## Thresholds

* Account quota is 50000 events/sec
* Yellow is > 35000 aka 70%
* Red is a breach

Yellow is 70% our quota and lets us continue using SNS while we raise a support request with AWS. It also gives as an opportunity to implement throttling on event ingest without errors being thrown by Lambda.

tiles.name: Markdown
tiles.markdown:
## Explanation

Usage against various Firehose quotas which are

* 100000 records per second
* 1000 requests per second
* 1MB per second

If any of these metrics are breached Firehose cannot deliver events, which affects our fraud and performance analytics capability.

## Thresholds

* Yellow is > 70%
* Red is a breach

This gives us enough time to raise a quota limit with AWS or reduce the rate of ingest.

tiles.name: Markdown
tiles.markdown:
## Explanation

Age (from getting into Amazon Data Firehose to now) of the oldest record in Amazon Data Firehose. 

Any record older than this age has been delivered to Splunk.

If the latency gets too high, then this is an indication that firehose is not sending data to Splunk fast enough then either firehose or Splunk setting need to be changed.

tiles.name: Markdown
tiles.markdown:
## Thresholds

* Yellow is > 2 minutes
* Red is > 4 minutes

No actual SLAs have been defined but this is a _reasonable_ amount of latency for the bulk delivery of events.

tiles.name: Markdown
tiles.markdown:
## Explanation

Time taken for an event to be placed in the self serve consumer's output queue based on the timestamp on the event, i.e. how long it takes TxMA to deliver a message to internal users.

This can hint towards capacity problems if latency trends upwards.

## Thresholds

* Yellow is > 250ms
* Red is > 500ms

No SLA has been set by TxMA or event consumers - these values are based on historical data.

set no thresholds as consumers can consume when they are ready. no SLA has been set. safety over speed
